{{ZenBuddhism}}
[[Zen]] has a rich doctrinal background, despite the traditional Zen narrative which states that it is a "special transmission outside scriptures" which "did not stand upon words."{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A|p=85-94}}

==Polarities==
Classical Chinese Chán is characterised by a set of polarities:{{sfn|McRae|2003|pp=138–142}} absolute-relative,<ref name="Liang-Chieh 1986 9">{{Harvcolnb|Liang-Chieh|1986|p=9}}</ref> Buddha-nature - sunyata,{{sfn|Kasulis|2003|pp=26–29}} sudden and gradual enlightenment,{{sfn|McRae|2003|pp=123–138}} esoteric and exoteric transmission.{{sfn|Borup|2008|p=9}}

===Absolute-relative===
The [[Prajnaparamita|Prajnaparamita-sutras]]  and [[Madhyamaka]] emphasized the non-duality of form and emptiness: "form is emptiness, emptiness is form", as the [[heart sutra]] says.<ref name="Liang-Chieh 1986 9"/> 
This was understood to mean that ultimate reality is not a transcendental realm, but equal to the daily world of relative reality. This idea fitted into the Chinese culture, which emphasized the mundane world and society. But this does not tell how the absolute is present in the relative world:
{{quote|To deny the duality of samsara and nirvana, as the Perfection of Wisdom does, or to demonstrate logically the error of dichotomizing conceptualization, as Nagarjuna does, is not to address the question of the relationship between samsara and nirvana -or, in more philosophical terms, between phenomenal and ultimate reality [...] What, then, is the relationship between these two realms?<ref name="Liang-Chieh 1986 9"/>}}
This question is answered in such schemata as [[Five Ranks|the Five Ranks of Tozan]],<ref>{{Harvcolnb|Kasulis|2003|p=29}}</ref> the [[Ten Bulls|Oxherding Pictures]], and [[Hakuin#Four ways of knowing|Hakuin's Four ways of knowing]].{{sfn|Low|2006}}

The [[Madhyamaka|Madhyamaka-scheme]] of the [[Two Truths doctrine]], and the [[Yogacara|Yogacara-schemes]] of the [[Three natures|Three Natures]] and the [[Trikaya|Trikaya-doctrine]], also give depictions of the interplay between the absolute and the relative.

===Buddha-nature and sunyata===
When Buddhism was introduced in China it was understood in terms of its own culture. Various sects struggled to attain an understanding of the Indian texts. The [[Tathāgatagarbha Sutras]] and the idea of the [[Buddha-nature]] were endorsed, because of the perceived similarities with the [[Tao]], which was understood as a transcendental reality underlying the world of appearances. [[Sunyata]] at first was understood as pointing to the Taoist [[Mu (negative)|"wu"]], ''nothingness''.{{sfn|Lai|Year unknown}}{{sfn|Swanson|1993|p=373}}

The doctrine of the Buddha-nature asserts that all [[Sentient beings (Buddhism)|sentient beings]] have [[Buddha-nature]] (Skt. ''Buddhadhātu'', "Buddha Element", "Buddha-Principle"), the element from which awakening springs. The [[Tathāgatagarbha Sutras]] (literally: the womb of the thus-gone) state that every living being has the potential to realize awakening.{{sfn|Wayman|1990}} Hence Buddhism offers salvation to every-one, not only to monks or those who have freed themselves almost completely from karma in previous lives.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}} The  [[Yogacara]] theory of the [[Eight Consciousnesses]] explains how sensory input and the mind create the world we experience, and obscure the alaya-vijnana, which is equated to the Buddha-nature.{{sfn|Kalupahana|1992}}

When this potential is realized, and the defilements have been eliminated, the tathagatagarbha manifests as the [[Dharmakaya]], the absolute reality which pervades everything in the world.{{sfn|Wayman|1990}} In this way, it is also the primordial reality from which phenomenal reality springs. When this understanding is idealized, it becomes a transcendental reality beneath the world of appearances.{{sfn|Kalupahan|1994}}

Sunyata points to the "emptiness" or no-"thing"-ness of all "things". Though we perceive a world of concrete and discrete objects, designated by names, on close analysis the "thingness" dissolves, leaving them "empty" of inherent existence.{{sfn|Kalupahan|1994|p=160-169}} The [[Heart sutra]], a text from the [[Prajnaparamita|prajnaparamita-sutras]], articulates this in the following saying in which the [[Skandha|five skandhas]] are said to be "empty":
{{quote|"Oh, Sariputra, Form Does not Differ From the Void,<br/>
And the Void Does Not Differ From Form.<br/>
Form is Void and Void is Form;<br/>
The Same is True For Feelings,<br/>
Perceptions, Volitions and Consciousness".<ref group=web>[http://www.buddhanet.net/e-learning/heartstr.htm The Heart Sutra Prajna Paramita Hrydaya Sutra]</ref>}}
The teachings on the five skandhas belong to the central teachings in the [[Tripitaka]]. They form a subdivision of the [[Samyutta Nikaya#Divisions|Samyutta Nikaya]]. The five skandhas are also mentioned in the Lankavatara-sutra:
{{quote|The [[Citta]] dances like a dancer; [[Manas (early Buddhism)|the Manas]] resembles a jester; the [[Manas-vijnana|[Mano-]vijnana]] together with the [[Eight Consciousnesses|five [Vijnanas]]] creates an objective world which is like a stage.<ref group=web name=Lanka>[http://lirs.ru/do/lanka_eng/lanka-nondiacritical.htm Lankavatara Sutra, chapter LXXXII, p.192 Suzuki-translation, p.223/224 in brackets]</ref>{{refn|group=note|The influence of these teachings can be seen in the sayings of Mazu:<br/>
Master Liang visited Ma-tsu.<br/>
Ma-tsu said: I heard that the master is great at explaining the sutras and sastras, is that so?<br/>
Liang said: Indeed<br/>
Ma-tsu said: With what do you explain?<br/>
Liang said: I explain with the mind<br/>
Ma-tsu said: The mind is like an artist and consciousness is [like] his helper, how can you explain the teachings with that?{{sfn|Lievens|1981|p=§19, p.105-106 }}}}}}

The [[Yogacara]] explains this "emptiness" in an analysis of the way we perceive "things". Everything we conceive of is the result of the working of the [[Skandha|five skandhas]]—results of perception, feeling, volition, and discrimination.{{refn|group=note|Translations do differ, which makes a difference. [[Vijñāna]] can be translated as "consciousness", but also as "discernment".{{sfn|Kalupahana|1992}}}} The five skandhas together compose consciousness. The "things" we are conscious of are "mere concepts", not ''[[Noumenon|Ding an sich]]''.{{sfn|Kalupahana|1992}}

It took [[Chinese Buddhism]] several centuries to recognize that [[sunyata]] does not refer to "wu", ''nothingness'',{{sfn|Lai|Year unknown}}{{sfn|Swanson|1993}} nor does Buddhism postulate an undying soul.{{sfn|Lai|Year unknown}} The influence of those various doctrinal and textual backgrounds is still discernible in Zen. Zen teachers still refer to Buddha-nature, but the Zen tradition also emphasizes that Buddha-nature ''is'' sunyata, the absence of an independent and substantial self.{{sfn|Lai|Year unknown}}

===Sudden and gradual enlightenment===
[[File:Kano White-robed Kannon, Bodhisattva of Compassion.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Avalokiteśvara]] Bodhisattva sitting in meditation]]

In Zen Buddhism two main views on the way to enlightenment are discernible, namely [[Subitism|sudden]] and gradual enlightenment.

Early Chán recognized the ''"transcendence of the body and mind"'', followed by ''"non-defilement [of] knowledge and perception"'', meaning [[Kensho|sudden insight into the true nature]] followed by gradual purification of intentions.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=88-92}}

In the 8th-century the Ch'an-history was effectively re-fashioned by [[Shenhui]], who created a dichotomy between the so-called [[East Mountain Teaching|"Northern School"]], led by [[Yuquan Shenxiu]], and his own line of teaching, which he called the "Southern school".{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=54-56}} Shenhui placed [[Hui-neng]] into prominence as the sixth Chán-patriarch, and emphasized ''sudden enlightenment'', as opposed to the concurrent Northern School's alleged ''gradual enlightenment''.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=54-56}} According to the ''sudden enlightenment'' propagated by Shenhui insight into true nature is sudden; thereafter there can be no misunderstanding anymore about this true nature.

In the [[Platform Sutra]] the dichotomy between sudden and gradual is reconciled.{{sfn|MacRae|2003|p=60-67}} [[Guifeng Zongmi]], fifth-generation successor to Shenhui, also softened the edge between sudden and gradual. In his analysis, sudden awakening points to seeing into one's true nature, but is to be followed by a gradual cultivation to attain [[Buddhahood]].{{sfn|Gregory|1991}}

[[Jinul|Chinul]], a 12th-century Korean Seon master, followed Zongmi, and also emphasized that insight into our true nature is sudden, but is to be followed by practice to ripen the insight and attain full Buddhahood. This is also the standpoint of the contemporary [[Sanbo Kyodan]], according to whom kensho is at the start of the path to full  enlightenment.{{sfn|Kapleau|1989}}

This gradual cultivation is also recognized by [[Tozan]], who described the [[Five Ranks|Five ranks of enlightenment]].<ref group=web>[http://awakeningtoreality.blogspot.nl/2008/02/tozan-ryokais-verses-on-five-ranks.html The Five Ranks of Tozan]</ref> Other example of depiction of stages on the path are the [[Ten Bulls|Ten Ox-Herding Pictures]] which detail the steps on the Path, [[Linji Yixuan#Expressing the inexpressible|The Three mysterious Gates]] of Linji, and the [[Hakuin#Four ways of knowing|Four Ways of Knowing]] of [[Hakuin]].{{sfn|Low|2006}} This gradual cultivation is described by Chan Master Sheng Yen as follows:
{{quote|Ch'an expressions refer to enlightenment as "seeing your self-nature". But even this is not enough. After seeing your self-nature, you need to deepen your experience even further and bring it into maturation. You should have enlightenment experience again and again and support them with continuous practice. Even though Ch'an says that at the time of enlightenment, your outlook is the same as of the Buddha, you are not yet a [[Buddhahood|full Buddha]].{{sfn|Yen|2006|p=54)}}}}

The emphasis which Shenhui placed on [[Subitism|sudden enlightenment]], also reflected a growing appreciation of the [[Diamond Sutra]] in 8th-century Chinese Buddhism.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=62}}{{sfn|Kasulis|2003|pp=26–28}} The Lankavatara-sutra, which endorses the Buddha-nature, emphasized purity of mind, which can be attained in gradations. The Diamond-sutra emphasizes sunyata, which "must be realized  totally or not at all".{{sfn|Kasulis|2003|pp=26–28}}

Once the dichotomy between sudden and gradual was in place, it defined its own logic and rhetorics, which are also recognizable in the distinction between Caodong (Soto) and Lin-ji (Rinzai) chán.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=123}} But it also leads to a "sometimes bitter and always prolix sectarian controversy between later Chán and [[Huayan school|Hua-yen]] exegetes".{{sfn|Buswell|1993|p=234}} In the [[Huayan school#Classification of Buddhist teachings|Huayan classification of teachings]], the sudden approach was regarded inferior to the Perfect Teaching of Hua-yen. [[Guifeng Zongmi]], fifth patriarch of Hua-yen ànd Chán-master, devised his [[Guifeng Zongmi#The Buddha's Teachings|own classification]] to counter this subordination.{{sfn|Gregory|1991}} To establish the superiority of the Chán-teachings, Chinul explained the sudden approach as not pointing to mere emptiness, but to ''suchness'' or the [[dharmadhatu]].{{sfn|Buswell|1991|p=240-241}}

===Esoteric and exoteric transmission===
According to Borup the emphasis on 'mind to mind transmission' is a form of esoteric transmission, in which "the tradition and the enlightened mind is transmitted face to face".{{sfn|Borup|2008|p=9}} Metaphorically this can be described as the transmission from a flame from one candle to another candle,{{sfn|Borup|2008|p=9}} or the transmission from one vein to another.{{sfn|Faure|2000|p=58}} In exoteric transmission requires "direct access to the teaching through a personal discovery of one's self. This type of transmission and identification is symbolized by the discovery of a shining lantern, or a mirror."{{sfn|Borup|2008|p=9}}

This polarity is recognizable in the emphasis that the Zen-tradition puts on maintaining the correct [[Dharma transmission]], while simultaneously stressing seeing into one's nature:
{{quote|The matter of learning from a teacher is most essential. People of old who arrived at the source of [[Kensho|seeing nature]], passed through many barriers clearly and completely without a dot of doubt, and traveled freely through the world opening big mouths in discussion, only came to know the transcendental message of Zen after they finally ran into Zen masters of great vision. Then they sincerely sought certainty and wound up with the duty of the teacher's succession, bearing the debt of Dharma, never to forget it for a moment. This is called dharma succession. Since ancient times the designated succession of the ancestral teachers has always been like this.{{sfn|Torei|2010|p=88}}{{refn|group=note|The modern framing of Zen as the ''experience'' of 'ultimate truth' or reality{{sfn|Sharf|2005-B}} may influence the institutional shape western Zen is going to take, where individual freedom is highly appraised. See also Bodiford 2008, pp 277-279}}}}

Nevertheless, while the Zen tradition has always stressed the importance of formal Dharma transmission, there are well known examples of [[Mushi dokugo]], such as [[Nōnin]], [[Jinul]] and [[Suzuki Shōsan]] who attained awakening on their own, though all of them were familiair with the Zen-teachings.

==The Bodhisattva ideal==
{{main article|Bodhisattva}}

An important, though easily overlooked aspect of Zen is the bodhisattva ideal.{{sfn|Batchelor|2004}} It supplements [[kensho]] and insight into the [[Dharmadhatu|absolute]] with [[Karuṇā]], compassion with all sentient beings.{{sfn|Low|2006}} This ideal is reflected in the [[Bodhisattva vow]] and the [[Bodhisattva Precepts]]{{sfn|Anderson|2000}} or [[jukai]].<ref group=web>[http://www.thezensite.com/ZenTeachings/Dogen_Teachings/Shobogenzo/083jukai.pdf Dogen, ''On Receiving the Precepts'']</ref>

Part of this Bodhisattva-ideal are the [[pāramitā]]s, which are also being mentioned in the Diamond Sutra: 
* [[Dāna]] (generosity, giving of oneself),
* [[Śīla]] (virtue, morality, proper conduct),
* [[Kṣānti]] (patience, tolerance, forbearance, acceptance, endurance),
* [[Vīrya]] (energy, diligence, vigour, effort),
* [[Dhyāna in Buddhism|Dhyāna]] (meditation, tranquility), and
* [[Wisdom in Buddhism|Prajñā]] (wisdom, insight).{{sfn|Wai-tao|1994}}{{refn|group=note|Wai-tao and Goddard re-arranged their translation of the Diamond Sutra topically, using the six paramitas as a framework{{sfn|Aitken|1994}}}}

The Bodhisattva-ideal is a central theme in the prajnaparamita-sutras.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A|p=41}}

Dogen mentions the Bodhisattva-ideal throughout his works.<ref group=web>[http://www.thezensite.com/ZenTeachings/Dogen_Teachings/Shobogenzo/032kannon.pdf Dogen, Sobogenzo, ''On Kannon, the Bodhisattva of Compassion'']</ref><ref group=web>[http://www.thezensite.com/ZenTeachings/Dogen_Teachings/Shobogenzo/046bodaisattaShishobo.pdf dogen, Shobogenzo, ''On the Four Exemplary Acts of a Bodhisattva'']</ref>

[[Hakuin]] saw "deep compassion and commitment to help all sentient beings everywhere"{{sfn|Low|2006|p=35}} as an indispensable part of the [[Hakuin#Four ways of knowing|Buddhist path to awakening]]. Hakuin emphasized the need of "post-satori training",{{sfn|Waddell|2010}}{{sfn|Hakuin|2010}} purifying the mind of karmic tendencies and 
{{quote|[W]hipping forward the wheel of the Four Universal Vows, pledging yourself to benefit and save all sentient beings while striving every minute of your life to practice the great Dharma giving.{{sfn|Hakuin|2010}}}}

The insight in the need of arousing [[bodhicitta]] formed Hakuin's final awakening:
{{quote|Wasn't a shaven head and monk's robe the Mind of Enlightenment? Wasn't reciting sutras, mantras, and dharanis the Mind of Enlightenment? [...] [At] my forty-first year, [...] I at long last penetrated into the heart of this great matter. Suddenly, unexpectedly, I saw it — it was as clear as if it were right there in the hollow of my hand. What is the Mind of Enlightenment? It is, I realized, a matter of doing good — benefiting others by giving them the gift of the Dharma teaching.{{sfn|Hakuin|2010}}}}

Buddhas and bodhisattvas such as [[Amitabha|Amitābha]], [[Avalokitesvara|Avalokiteśvara]], [[Manjusri|Mañjuśrī]], [[Samantabhadra]], and [[Ksitigarbha|Kṣitigarbha]] are venerated alongside [[Shakyamuni Buddha|Gautama Buddha]].<ref>{{Harvcolnb|Lathouwers|2000}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|{{sfn|Lathouwers|2000|p=221}} mentions: Blofeld, John (1988), ''Bodhisattva of compassion - the mystical tradition of kuan Yin''. Boston: Shanbhala}}

By repeatedly chanting the {{Nihongo|Avalokiteshvara sutra|観世音菩薩普門品|Kanzeon Bosatsu Fumonbon}} (chapter 25 of the Lotus Sutra<ref group=web>[http://zen.rinnou.net/whats_zen/sacred_texts.html#Avalokite%C5%9Bvara%20Sutra Avalokiteśvara Sutra]</ref>), for example, one instills the Bodhisattva's ideals into one's mind. The ultimate goal is given in the end of the sutra, which states, "In the morning, be one with [[Avalokiteshvara]]; in the evening, be one with Avalokiteshvara". Through the realization of [[Shunyata|emptiness]] and the Mahayana notion that all things have [[Buddha-nature]], one understands that there is no difference between the cosmic bodhisattva and oneself. The wisdom and compassion of the Bodhisattva one is chanting to is seen to equal the inner wisdom and compassion of the practitioner. Thus, the duality between subject and object, practitioner and Bodhisattva, chanter and sutra is ended.

