'''Pioneer Valley Zendo''' is a [[Soto Zen]] [[zendo]] established in 1976 in [[Charlemont, Massachusetts]], United States, as a sister-temple to [[Antai-ji]] in Japan,<ref name="amonk">{{cite web|last=Braverman|first=Arthur|authorlink=Arthur Braverman|title=A Monk and a Zendo|url=http://buddhismnow.com/2013/12/11/a-monk-and-a-zendo-by-arthur-braverman/|publisher=Buddhism Now|date=December 11, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> where [[Kosho Uchiyama]] was [[rōshi]].
==History== In 1974, Steve Yenik and [[Koshi Ichida]] arrived from Japan<ref name="valleyzendo">{{cite web|title=Valley Zendo|url=http://global.sotozen-net.or.jp/eng/temples/outside_jp/America/8.html|publisher=[[Sōtō#Organisation|Sotoshu]]|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> and began raising funds to create a zendo in the forest hills near the Vermont border.<ref name="amonk"/><ref name="valleyzendo"/> Ichida was joined by [[Eishin Ikeda]] and [[Shohaku Okumura]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zendo History|url=http://www.valleyzendo.org/history.htm|publisher=Valley Zendo|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> [[Reverend]] [[Issho Fujita]] was the resident teacher from 1987 until 2005.<ref name="valleyzendo"/> Eishin Ikeda, who later led the Bean Town Sangha (founded by Eishin Ikeda and [[Michael Flessas]]) whose first meetings were held on the second floor of a book store in Arlington, Massachusetts, returned as the present resident priest in 2006.<ref name="valleyzendo"/>
